x4freetext: Measurement of cross sections for inelastic
cold-neutron scattering in metals and polymers by
method of (n,gamma) analysis.
P.Geltenbort .
S.S.Arzumanov,L.N.Bondarenko,V.I.Morozov,
Yu.N.Panin, S.M.Chernyavskiy .
ILL High Flux reactor .
Ultra cold neutrons of energy 50-200 neV come
from TGV source of the ILL High Flux reactor to the
spectrum shaper, which wall is coated by Fomblin oil
with limited energy 106 neV. Leaving the shaper with
energy 50-106 neV and accelerating in vertical neutron
guide 150 or 200 cm long and made of Ni, neutrons of
energy 200-255 or 250-305 neV hit the plane sample of
total absorption placed in the chamber.
He-3 filled neutron detector to control the
neutron flux and its absorption.
Ge(HP)- gamma-ray detector of energy resolution
2.5 keV for 661-keV gamma-rays. At 15 cm distance from
sample center.
The capture event is accompanied by prompt
characteristic gamma-rays with the known energies, that
correspond to isotopes composed the sample.
The up-scattering event transfers VCN into thermal
neutron that flies away the sample and then being
captured by B-10-converter generates gamma-ray of
477 keV at reaction B-10(N,A+G)Li-7 .
SET-up calibration was made with Al-sample 2mm thick,
fluorine substituted oil by using 477 keV gamma-peak of
polyethylene by using 2223 keV gamma-peak of (npdgamma)
reaction.
Neutron inelastic scattering cross section is deduced
from the ratio of registered counts of capture and
up-scattering events using the known capture cross
section for basic isotopes of the sample.
Solid samples as disks of 7 cm diameter, mounted into
a cooled copper ring onto a stainless steel foil of
100 microm thick, to which a converter as disk from
boron-containing rubber of 10 mm thick was pressed.
The sample temperature was preset between 300 and
100 K by varying the rate of liquid-nitrogen injection
into the cooling spiral of copper ring.
Liquid sample: liquid was poured directly onto the
foil pressed tightly to the copper-ring plane
with boron-containing rubber.
The thickness of samples was chosen to ensure a
complete absorption of the incident neutron flux in
sample.
29.01.2008 from L.N.Bondarenko.

Data of the nickel isotopic composition and the
capture cross sections of these isotopes in thermal
region were taken into account.Measured counting rates
for gamma rays emitted in the main transitions
following neutron capture on Ni-58 isotope and the
corresponding gamma-ray yields per neutron capture
event were used to determine inelastic cross section.
